Why Merkle trees? Show how a Merkle tree enables efficient membership proofs (SPV-style idea) and what breaks if you used just “hash(all txns)” without a tree

    Merkle trees exist because you want two things at once:

        1. the block header should contain one small commitment to all transactions
        2. later, you should be able to prove “this transaction is in that block” without sending the whole block

    How a Merkle tree gives efficient membership proofs (SPV idea)

        * Each transaction is hashed → these hashes are the leaves
        * Pairwise hash upward until one hash remains → Merkle root
        * The Merkle root goes in the block header (which PoW commits to)

    Now, to prove a specific transaction (Tx) is included, you don’t send all transactions. You send a Merkle proof:

        * h = H(Tx)
        * the sibling hashes along the path from that leaf to the root (one hash per tree level)

    The verifier (SPV client) does:

        * combine (h) with sibling hash level by level until you end up with a single computed root
        * check if it equals the header’s Merkle root

    Proof size: about log2(n) hashes for n transactions.
    So for 2,048 txns, the proof is 11 hashes — tiny.

    That’s the SPV-style win: a light client can download block headers + one Merkle proof, instead of full blocks.

    What breaks if you used just “hash(all txns)” (a flat hash)

    Suppose your commitment is:
    [R] = H(Tx1 || Tx2 || ............ || Txn)
    

    To prove (Tx_k) is included, the verifier needs to recompute R. But to recompute R, they need all transactions.

    That kills the light-client model:

        * No small proofs
        * No efficient “give me just enough to verify my payment”
        * Bandwidth and storage increases.


Desirable properties of money: Explain fungibility, durability, portability (censorship resistance), divisibility, scarcity—and connect each to Bitcoin’s design claims.

   Bitcoin’s core claim is that cryptography + distributed consensus can deliver money-like properties without relying on a central issuer

    Fungibility: Any unit of money is interchangeable with any other unit of the same face value.

        Bitcoin design connection:

            * The protocol doesn’t attach “quality grades” to coins. 1 BTC is nominally the same as any other.
        
    Durability: Money should not physically degrade, and the record of ownership should persist.

        Bitcoin design connection:

            * Value is controlled by cryptographic keys and the ledger is duplicated across many nodes, so it doesn’t rely on any single system to survive.
            * Each block commits to the previous block, making edits obvious, and ongoing block production keeps the record current and consistent.

    Portability: Money should move easily across distance/time, and ideally transfers shouldn’t require permission.

        Bitcoin design connection:

            * Anyone can create an address and move value by broadcasting a signed transaction as there is no account setup or a central operator.
            * Transactions propagate via the P2P network and get confirmed by miners per consensus rules as there is no single choke point or approve/deny authority.

    Divisibility: Money should support small and large payments precisely.

        Bitcoin design connection:

            * 1 BTC = 100,000,000 satoshis, so it’s highly divisible at the protocol level.

    Scarcity: Supply should be limited or predictably constrained so it can’t be inflated at will.

        Bitcoin design connection:

            * Keeps block production roughly steady over time, so issuance follows schedule rather than speeding up when more miners join.
            * Capped total supply 21M BTC enforced by consensus rules.
            * Block subsidy decreases on a fixed schedule, reducing new supply rate over time.
            * S/F ratio tends to infinity overtime.

Define money’s 3 roles (medium of exchange, unit of account, store of value) and argue where Bitcoin fits well vs poorly.
    
    Money’s 3 roles

        * Medium of exchange: Money is the thing people actually use to pay for goods/services.

        * Unit of account: Money is standard measure of value. Salaries, invoices, accounting books are denominated in it.

        * Store of value: Money allows value to be stored overtime to be spent at liesure.

    Where Bitcoin fits well vs poorly

        Medium of exchange

            * Fits well: Money settlement without relying on a specific institution especially cross border.
            * Fits poorly: For everyday payments on the base layer because it can be slow/fees vary.

        Unit of account

            * Fits poorly (today): most prices and contracts aren’t denominated in BTC.
            * Fits better (niche): crypto-native ecosystems where BTC is a common reference asset.

        Store of value

            * Fits well: supply is predictable and capped, so it’s designed to be scarce.
            * Fits poorly: price swings a lot, so your buying power can change quickly




